  "articleSummary": "The article argues that modern supply chain attacks exploit developer trust, turning local machines into \"credential warehouses\" that can be drained by a single bad click. It analyzes how infostealers like Lumma Stealer and the Mandiant Snowflake investigation reveal that attackers reuse stolen credentials from years-old exposures, making local isolation the critical defense. Written in an urgent, practical tone for developers, it advocates for Dev Containers (to filesystem-isolate project work), canary tokens (to detect reconnaissance), and secret scoping as high-leverage moves. Recurring metaphors—\"credential warehouse,\" \"dye pack,\" and \"boundaries vs. traffic\"—frame the problem as structural rather than behavioral, rejecting \"be careful\" as a non-solution.",
